19
00:01:54,000 --> 00:02:04,000
I thought I might start with inviting you just to share some reflections of coming up and saying Augustine and maybe a little bit about family and schooling.

20
00:02:04,000 --> 00:02:12,000
That will sort of help us set the stage for how you emerge as activists in your teenage years.

21
00:02:12,000 --> 00:02:24,000
Well, coming up in Synalgusting, Synalgusting to me was a very, very nice, nice town to live in.

22
00:02:24,000 --> 00:02:30,000
To grow up in, we had a lot of black businesses at the time that I grew up.

23
00:02:30,000 --> 00:02:36,000
Washington Street was all remain, street that had a lot of black businesses.

24
00:02:36,000 --> 00:02:49,000
And when we started in the movement, we didn't start off picketing or demonstrating.

25
00:02:49,000 --> 00:03:00,000
We would go down to the St. Paul's AME Church and sit around and just talk about what we were going to do.

26
00:03:00,000 --> 00:03:04,000
You know, that was when school was out.

27
00:03:04,000 --> 00:03:16,000
And when we found out that we had someone, a leader that would back us in a way that we never would have dreamed of.

28
00:03:16,000 --> 00:03:20,000
Because most of the leaders would tell us, no, you can't do that.

29
00:03:20,000 --> 00:03:23,000
That's not the way you do it.

30
00:03:23,000 --> 00:03:25,000
You got to wait.

31
00:03:25,000 --> 00:03:32,000
But Dr. Harvey Haley, he was our advisor, youth advisor.

32
00:03:32,000 --> 00:03:39,000
And he just motivated us to want to go and make a difference in Synalgusting.

33
00:03:39,000 --> 00:03:51,000
Because for me, I didn't too much care about my mom having to come and buy my school supplies at Woodworth.

34
00:03:51,000 --> 00:03:55,000
Because at that time, there was not no Wal-Martin.

35
00:03:55,000 --> 00:03:59,000
It was just a downtown area with Woodworth and Macquarie's.

36
00:03:59,000 --> 00:04:02,000
And they were about our school supplies there.

37
00:04:02,000 --> 00:04:06,000
And there was a lunch counter over there.

38
00:04:06,000 --> 00:04:11,000
And she would go in, come walkin' through the park,

39
00:04:11,000 --> 00:04:14,000
and had to pass the fountain in the park.

40
00:04:14,000 --> 00:04:18,000
Because it had white only on it.

41
00:04:18,000 --> 00:04:22,000
And she would go over there and buy my school supplies.

42
00:04:22,000 --> 00:04:30,000
And she would also buy, you know, little accessories that you needed, you know, for school.

43
00:04:30,000 --> 00:04:33,000
But she couldn't go over and get a drink of water.

44
00:04:33,000 --> 00:04:36,000
I had a problem with that.

45
00:04:36,000 --> 00:04:41,000
And I said to myself, you know, there's something wrong with this picture.

46
00:04:41,000 --> 00:04:49,000
So when I seen the young people gathering up at this church down the street from me,

47
00:04:49,000 --> 00:04:52,000
I saw them go down there and see what they're doing.

48
00:04:52,000 --> 00:04:55,000
But all they were doing was just gathering.

49
00:04:55,000 --> 00:05:06,000
And Mr. Clyde Jenkins, Dr. Helen, Mr. Lucille Plummer, and Miss Fanny Wood, Fuller Wood,

50
00:05:06,000 --> 00:05:11,000
they started bringing up supplies to make picket signs.

51
00:05:11,000 --> 00:05:18,000
So we made our little picket signs and we would go downtown every day.

52
00:05:18,000 --> 00:05:25,000
Every day, every morning, we would meet at St. Paul and get our picket signs

53
00:05:25,000 --> 00:05:32,000
and go to the world, some would go to the Armacurus, and some would go to Woolworth,

54
00:05:32,000 --> 00:05:38,000
some would go to the little local drug stores that was down in the area,

55
00:05:38,000 --> 00:05:43,000
and picket maybe two or three at one place, four or five at another, you know.

56
00:05:43,000 --> 00:05:53,000
And that's how we did it until one day we gathered at St. Paul Church and we said it was in July.

57
00:05:53,000 --> 00:05:55,000
And we said 1963.

58
00:05:55,000 --> 00:06:00,000
1963, July 1963, July 18th.

59
00:06:00,000 --> 00:06:06,000
And we said we were sitting around and we had some old tomatoes,

60
00:06:06,000 --> 00:06:13,000
and we were just sitting there like the name was Jimmy Jackson, Francis Floyd,

61
00:06:13,000 --> 00:06:17,000
and older people, older, older, older, older, older was,

62
00:06:17,000 --> 00:06:22,000
and we were just sitting there, car Williams, and we were just sitting there,

63
00:06:22,000 --> 00:06:27,000
and Francis Floyd said it's time for us to do something.

64
00:06:27,000 --> 00:06:29,000
We got to talk to the doctor.

65
00:06:29,000 --> 00:06:32,000
We got to go and do something.

66
00:06:32,000 --> 00:06:38,000
We got to talk to the doctor and we were talking to him about the sickle of the city,

67
00:06:38,000 --> 00:06:45,000
so big Jimmy Jackson, there's a difference between, there's a little Jimmy Jackson,

68
00:06:45,000 --> 00:06:47,000
and there's a big Jimmy Jackson.

69
00:06:47,000 --> 00:06:53,000
There's a difference between them, and the big Jimmy Jackson said,

70
00:06:53,000 --> 00:06:57,000
well we going down town to city, and go to the city,

71
00:06:57,000 --> 00:06:59,000
I was going to go down town to city,

72
00:06:59,000 --> 00:07:04,640
So we put the signs up against the wall and walked downtown.

73
00:07:04,640 --> 00:07:07,340
We went down to Francis Street, turned down,

74
00:07:07,340 --> 00:07:08,860
watching to the street.

75
00:07:08,860 --> 00:07:11,320
And as we was going down in the little two,

76
00:07:11,320 --> 00:07:15,180
we was in twos, as we was walking down the street,

77
00:07:15,180 --> 00:07:19,080
Mr. Ernest Wells had a barber shop.

78
00:07:19,080 --> 00:07:25,200
And he came out because he was very involved in the NAACP.

79
00:07:25,200 --> 00:07:26,280
And he came out.

80
00:07:26,280 --> 00:07:29,840
He said, where you all think you're going?

81
00:07:29,840 --> 00:07:32,360
We said, we're going to set in.

82
00:07:32,360 --> 00:07:35,520
He said, who told you all the gold set in?

83
00:07:35,520 --> 00:07:37,520
Where's those picket signs?

84
00:07:37,520 --> 00:07:40,120
And we said, we left them at the church.

85
00:07:40,120 --> 00:07:41,640
We going to set in.

86
00:07:41,640 --> 00:07:47,600
He said, well, did Dr. Nol, he didn't?

87
00:07:47,600 --> 00:07:49,840
He said, well, do you have any money?

88
00:07:49,840 --> 00:07:51,720
And we said, no.

89
00:07:51,720 --> 00:07:53,440
And he went back in his barber shop.

90
00:07:53,440 --> 00:07:56,240
He said, you can't buy nothing if you don't have no money.

91
00:07:56,520 --> 00:08:01,920
So he gave, I think it was goldie, goldie, some money.

92
00:08:01,920 --> 00:08:04,800
And he gave big gymma Jackson some money.

93
00:08:04,800 --> 00:08:06,480
So we walked down down.

94
00:08:06,480 --> 00:08:09,440
We never left off a cane street that day.

95
00:08:09,440 --> 00:08:16,280
That was what, one, two, three, three.

96
00:08:16,280 --> 00:08:21,360
It was a service drug store, my cotton is drug store,

97
00:08:21,360 --> 00:08:24,080
and then woodwork.

98
00:08:24,200 --> 00:08:30,040
And we went in goldie in a,

99
00:08:30,040 --> 00:08:35,120
Francis in Jimmy in a, and a,

100
00:08:35,120 --> 00:08:38,480
Gurgine, they went in the service drug store.

101
00:08:38,480 --> 00:08:48,960
And goldie and Harold Jenkins and several more went into my cotton.

102
00:08:48,960 --> 00:08:53,960
Joanne, myself, will a call and say him.

103
00:08:53,960 --> 00:09:01,640
And Dolores and Rosemary and Harris went to woodwork.

104
00:09:01,640 --> 00:09:04,440
And that's where we sat in it.

105
00:09:04,440 --> 00:09:08,600
Would it be OK on Army, the stock, you set the stage so beautifully?

106
00:09:08,600 --> 00:09:10,000
Can I bring in this armor?

107
00:09:10,000 --> 00:09:11,360
And it will bring the worries together.

108
00:09:11,360 --> 00:09:12,760
Yes, go ahead on.

109
00:09:12,760 --> 00:09:13,760
With things really starting.

110
00:09:13,760 --> 00:09:14,760
Yes.

111
00:09:14,760 --> 00:09:15,760
OK.

112
00:09:15,760 --> 00:09:16,760
Thanks, started for me.

113
00:09:16,760 --> 00:09:18,320
I lived on the north side of town.

114
00:09:18,320 --> 00:09:19,440
I lived on the west side.

115
00:09:19,440 --> 00:09:22,640
That means across the track.

116
00:09:22,640 --> 00:09:25,560
And there weren't anything for black children to do

117
00:09:25,560 --> 00:09:29,680
because they didn't have any activities, nothing whatsoever.

118
00:09:29,680 --> 00:09:32,560
So I had to get permission because I had a sister

119
00:09:32,560 --> 00:09:36,000
live on the originale side where the church was two streets

120
00:09:36,000 --> 00:09:38,480
